=\"ph1\">\\&lt;</ph>T&gt;.TryPeek can return an erroneous null via its out parameter","pos":[0,82],"source":"95: ConcurrentQueue\\<T>.TryPeek can return an erroneous null via its out parameter"}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[74471,74478]},{"pos":[74479,74646],"content":"In some multi-threaded scenarios, <ph id=\"ph1\">`ConcurentQueue&lt;T&gt;.TryPeek`</ph> can return true, but populate the out parameter with a null value (instead of the correct, peeked value).","source":"In some multi-threaded scenarios, `ConcurentQueue<T>.TryPeek` can return true, but populate the out parameter with a null value (instead of the correct, peeked value)."},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[74651,74661]},{"content":"This issue is fixed in the .NET Framework 4.5.1.","pos":[74662,74710]},{"content":"Upgrading to that Framework will solve the issue.","pos":[74711,74760]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[74765,74770]},{"content":"Major","pos":[74771,74776]},{"content":"Version","pos":[74781,74788]},{"content":"4.5-4.5.1","pos":[74789,74798]},{"content":"Type","pos":[74803,74807]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[74808,74815]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[74820,74833]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[74941,74950]},{"content":"CD0095","pos":[74951,74957]},{"pos":[74998,75068],"content":"98: Multiple items in a single TableLayoutPanel cell may be rearranged","linkify":"98: Multiple items in a single TableLayoutPanel cell may be rearranged","nodes":[{"content":"98: Multiple items in a single TableLayoutPanel cell may be rearranged","pos":[0,70]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[75089,75096]},{"content":"In the .NET Framework 4.5, if multiple items are placed in the same TableLayoutPanel cell, they may be displayed in a different order than they were in the .NET Framework 4.0.","pos":[75097,75272]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[75277,75287]},{"content":"This behavior was reverted in a servicing update for the .NET Framework 4.5.","pos":[75288,75364]},{"content":"Please update the .NET Framework 4.5, or upgrade to .NET Framework 4.5.1 or later, to fix this issue.","pos":[75365,75466]},{"content":"Alternatively, avoid the ambiguous case of multiple items in the same TableLayourPanel cell.","pos":[75467,75559]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[75564,75569]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[75570,75575]},{"content":"Version","pos":[75580,75587]},{"content":"4.5-4.5","pos":[75588,75595]},{"content":"Type","pos":[75600,75604]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[75605,75612]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[75617,75630]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[75785,75794]},{"content":"CD0098","pos":[75795,75801]},{"pos":[75843,75963],"content":"100: Foreach iterator variable is now scoped within the iteration, so closure capturing semantics are different (in C#5)","linkify":"100: Foreach iterator variable is now scoped within the iteration, so closure capturing semantics are different (in C#5)","nodes":[{"content":"100: Foreach iterator variable is now scoped within the iteration, so closure capturing semantics are different (in C#5)","pos":[0,120]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[75984,75991]},{"content":"Beginning with C# 5 (Visual Studio 2012), foreach iterator variables are scoped within the iteration.","pos":[75992,76093]},{"content":"This can cause breaks if code was previously depending on the variables to not be included in the foreach's closure.","pos":[76094,76210]},{"content":"The symptom of this change will be that an iterator variable passed to a delagate will be treated as the value it had at the time the delegate was created, rather than the value it had at the time the delegate was invoked.","pos":[76211,76433]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[76438,76448]},{"content":"Ideally, code should be updated to expect the new compiler behavior.","pos":[76449,76517]},{"content":"If the old semantics are required, the iterator variable can be replaced with a separate variable which is explicitly placed outside of the loop's scope.","pos":[76518,76671]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[76676,76681]},{"content":"Major","pos":[76682,76687]},{"content":"Version","pos":[76692,76699]},{"content":"4.5","pos":[76700,76703]},{"content":"Type","pos":[76708,76712]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[76713,76724]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[76729,76738]},{"content":"CD0100","pos":[76739,76745]},{"pos":[76787,76850],"content":"101: HtmlTextWriter does not render \\`<br/\\>` element correctly","linkify":"101: HtmlTextWriter does not render \\`<br/\\>` element correctly","nodes":[{"content":"101: HtmlTextWriter does not render <ph id=\"ph1\">\\`</ph>&lt;br/<ph id=\"ph2\">\\&gt;</ph>` element correctly","pos":[0,63],"source":"101: HtmlTextWriter does not render \\`<br/\\>` element correctly"}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[76871,76878]},{"pos":[76879,77074],"content":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.6, calling <ph id=\"ph1\">`HtmlTextWriter.RenderBeginTag()`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`HtmlTextWriter.RenderEndTag()`</ph> with a <ph id=\"ph3\">`&lt;BR /&gt;`</ph> element will correctly insert only one <ph id=\"ph4\">`&lt;BR /&gt;`</ph> (instead of two)","source":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.6, calling `HtmlTextWriter.RenderBeginTag()` and `HtmlTextWriter.RenderEndTag()` with a `<BR />` element will correctly insert only one `<BR />` (instead of two)"},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[77079,77089]},{"content":"If an app depended on the extra <ph id=\"ph1\">`&lt;BR /&gt;`</ph> tag, <ph id=\"ph2\">`HtmlTextWriter.RenderBeginTag()`</ph> should be called a second time.","pos":[77090,77201],"source":"If an app depended on the extra `<BR />` tag, `HtmlTextWriter.RenderBeginTag()` should be called a second time."},{"content":"Note that this behavior change only affects apps that are targeting the .NET Framework 4.6, so another option is to target a previous version of the .NET Framework in order to get the old behavior.","pos":[77202,77399]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[77404,77409]},{"content":"Edge","pos":[77410,77414]},{"content":"Version","pos":[77419,77426]},{"content":"4.6","pos":[77427,77430]},{"content":"Type","pos":[77435,77439]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[77440,77451]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[77456,77469]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[77694,77703]},{"content":"CD0101","pos":[77704,77710]},{"pos":[77752,77889],"content":"104: Calling Items.Refresh on a WPF ListBox, ListView, or DataGrid with items selected can cause duplicate items to appear in the element","linkify":"104: Calling Items.Refresh on a WPF ListBox, ListView, or DataGrid with items selected can cause duplicate items to appear in the element","nodes":[{"content":"104: Calling Items.Refresh on a WPF ListBox, ListView, or DataGrid with items selected can cause duplicate items to appear in the element","pos":[0,137]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[77910,77917]},{"content":"In the .NET Framework 4.5, calling ListBox.Items.Refresh from code while items are selected in a ListBox can cause the selected items to be duplicated in the list.","pos":[77918,78081]},{"content":"A similar issue occurs with ListView and DataGrid.","pos":[78082,78132]},{"content":"This is fixed in the .NET Framework 4.6.","pos":[78133,78173]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[78178,78188]},{"content":"This issue may be worked around by programatically unselecting items before Refresh is called and then re-selecting them after the call is completed.","pos":[78189,78338]},{"content":"Alternatively, this issue has been fixed in the .NET Framework 4.6 and may be addressed by upgrading to that version of the .NET Framework.","pos":[78339,78478]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[78483,78488]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[78489,78494]},{"content":"Version","pos":[78499,78506]},{"content":"4.5-4.6","pos":[78507,78514]},{"content":"Type","pos":[78519,78523]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[78524,78531]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[78536,78549]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[78629,78638]},{"content":"CD0104","pos":[78639,78645]},{"pos":[78687,78794],"content":"105: ETW EventListeners do not capture events from providers with explicit keywords (like the TPL provider)","linkify":"105: ETW EventListeners do not capture events from providers with explicit keywords (like the TPL provider)","nodes":[{"content":"105: ETW EventListeners do not capture events from providers with explicit keywords (like the TPL provider)","pos":[0,107]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[78815,78822]},{"content":"ETW EventListeners with a blank keyword mask do not properly capture events from providers with explicit keywords.","pos":[78823,78937]},{"content":"In the .NET Framework 4.5, the TPL provider began providing explicit keywords and triggered this issue.","pos":[78938,79041]},{"content":"In the .NET Framework 4.6, EventListeners have been updated to no longer have this issue.","pos":[79042,79131]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[79136,79146]},{"content":"To work around this problem, replace calls to EnableEvents(eventSource, level) with calls to the EnableEvents overload that explicitly specifies the \"any keywords\" mask to use: <ph id=\"ph1\">`EnableEvents(eventSource, level, unchecked((EventKeywords)0xFFFFffffFFFFffff))`</ph>.","pos":[79147,79405],"source":"To work around this problem, replace calls to EnableEvents(eventSource, level) with calls to the EnableEvents overload that explicitly specifies the \"any keywords\" mask to use: `EnableEvents(eventSource, level, unchecked((EventKeywords)0xFFFFffffFFFFffff))`."},{"content":"Alternatively, this issue has been fixed in the .NET Framework 4.6 and may be addressed by upgrading to that version of the .NET Framework.","pos":[79418,79557]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[79562,79567]},{"content":"Edge","pos":[79568,79572]},{"content":"Version","pos":[79577,79584]},{"content":"4.5-4.6","pos":[79585,79592]},{"content":"Type","pos":[79597,79601]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[79602,79609]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[79614,79627]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[79802,79811]},{"content":"CD0105","pos":[79812,79818]},{"pos":[79860,80002],"content":"109: Building an Entity Framework edmx with Visual Studio 2013 can fail with error MSB4062 if using the EntityDeploySplit or EntityClean tasks","linkify":"109: Building an Entity Framework edmx with Visual Studio 2013 can fail with error MSB4062 if using the EntityDeploySplit or EntityClean tasks","nodes":[{"content":"109: Building an Entity Framework edmx with Visual Studio 2013 can fail with error MSB4062 if using the EntityDeploySplit or EntityClean tasks","pos":[0,142]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[80023,80030]},{"content":"MSBuild 12.0 tools (included in Visual Studio 2013) changed msbuild file locations, causing older Entity Framework targets files to be invalid.","pos":[80031,80174]},{"content":"The result is that <ph id=\"ph1\">`EntityDeploySplit`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`EntityClean`</ph> tasks fail because they are unable to find <ph id=\"ph3\">`Microsoft.Data.Entity.Build.Tasks.dll`</ph>.","pos":[80175,80315],"source":" The result is that `EntityDeploySplit` and `EntityClean` tasks fail because they are unable to find `Microsoft.Data.Entity.Build.Tasks.dll`."},{"content":"Note that this break is because of a toolset (msbuild/VS) change, not because of a .NET Framework change.","pos":[80316,80421]},{"content":"It will only occur when upgrading developer tools, not when merely upgrading the .NET Framework.","pos":[80422,80518]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[80523,80533]},{"content":"Entity Framework targets files are fixed to work with the new msbuild layout beginning in the .NET Framework 4.6.","pos":[80534,80647]},{"content":"Upgrading to that version of the Framework will fix this issue.","pos":[80648,80711]},{"content":"Alternatively, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>this<ept id=\"p1\">](http://stackoverflow.com/a/24249247/131944)</ept> workaround can be used to patch the targets files directly.","pos":[80712,80837],"source":" Alternatively, [this](http://stackoverflow.com/a/24249247/131944) workaround can be used to patch the targets files directly."},{"content":"Scope","pos":[80842,80847]},{"content":"Major","pos":[80848,80853]},{"content":"Version","pos":[80858,80865]},{"content":"4.5.1-4.6","pos":[80866,80875]},{"content":"Type","pos":[80880,80884]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[80885,80896]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[80901,80910]},{"content":"CD0109","pos":[80911,80917]},{"pos":[80959,81087],"content":"111: XSD Schema validation now correctly detects violations of unique constraints if compound keys are used and one key is empty","linkify":"111: XSD Schema validation now correctly detects violations of unique constraints if compound keys are used and one key is empty","nodes":[{"content":"111: XSD Schema validation now correctly detects violations of unique constraints if compound keys are used and one key is empty","pos":[0,128]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[81108,81115]},{"content":"Versions of the .NET Framework prior to 4.6 had a bug that caused XSD validation to not detect unique constraints on compound keys if one of the keys was empty.","pos":[81116,81276]},{"content":"In the .NET Framework 4.6, this issue is corrected.","pos":[81277,81328]},{"content":"This will result in more correct validation, but it may also result in some XML not validating which previously would have.","pos":[81329,81452]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[81457,81467]},{"content":"If looser, .NET Framework 4.0 validation is needed, the validating application can target version 4.5 (or earlier) of the .NET Framework.","pos":[81468,81605]},{"content":"When retargeting to .NET 4.6, however, code review should be done to be sure that duplicate compound keys (as described in this issue's description) are not expected to validate.","pos":[81606,81784]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[81789,81794]},{"content":"Edge","pos":[81795,81799]},{"content":"Version","pos":[81804,81811]},{"content":"4.6","pos":[81812,81815]},{"content":"Type","pos":[81820,81824]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[81825,81836]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[81841,81850]},{"content":"CD0111","pos":[81851,81857]},{"pos":[81899,82054],"content":"112: Calling Attribute.GetCustomAttributes on an indexer property no longer throws AmbiguousMatchException if the ambiguity can be resolved by index's type","linkify":"112: Calling Attribute.GetCustomAttributes on an indexer property no longer throws AmbiguousMatchException if the ambiguity can be resolved by index's type","nodes":[{"content":"112: Calling Attribute.GetCustomAttributes on an indexer property no longer throws AmbiguousMatchException if the ambiguity can be resolved by index's type","pos":[0,155]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[82075,82082]},{"content":"Prior to the .NET Framework 4.6, calling <ph id=\"ph1\">`GetCustomAttribute(s)`</ph> on an indexer property which differed from another property only by the type of the index would result in an <ph id=\"ph2\">`AmbiguousMatchException`</ph>.","pos":[82083,82283],"source":"Prior to the .NET Framework 4.6, calling `GetCustomAttribute(s)` on an indexer property which differed from another property only by the type of the index would result in an `AmbiguousMatchException`."},{"content":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.6, the property's attributes will be correctly returned.","pos":[82284,82374]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[82379,82389]},{"content":"Be aware that GetCustomAttribute(s) will work more frequently now.","pos":[82390,82456]},{"content":"If an app was previously relying on the <ph id=\"ph1\">`AmbiguousMatchException`</ph>, reflection should now be used to explicitly look for multiple indexers, instead.","pos":[82457,82604],"source":" If an app was previously relying on the `AmbiguousMatchException`, reflection should now be used to explicitly look for multiple indexers, instead."},{"content":"Scope","pos":[82609,82614]},{"content":"Edge","pos":[82615,82619]},{"content":"Version","pos":[82624,82631]},{"content":"4.6","pos":[82632,82635]},{"content":"Type","pos":[82640,82644]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[82645,82652]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[82657,82670]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[85043,85052]},{"content":"CD0112","pos":[85053,85059]},{"pos":[85101,85229],"content":"113: Intermittently unable to scroll to bottom item in ItemsControls (like ListBox and DataGrid) when using custom DataTemplates","linkify":"113: Intermittently unable to scroll to bottom item in ItemsControls (like ListBox and DataGrid) when using custom DataTemplates","nodes":[{"content":"113: Intermittently unable to scroll to bottom item in ItemsControls (like ListBox and DataGrid) when using custom DataTemplates","pos":[0,128]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[85250,85257]},{"content":"In some instances, a bug in the .NET Framework 4.5 is causing ItemsControls (like ListBox, ComboBox, DataGrid, etc.) to not scroll to their bottom item when using custom DataTemplates.","pos":[85258,85442]},{"content":"If the scrolling is attempted a second time (after scrolling back up), it will work then.","pos":[85443,85532]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[85537,85547]},{"content":"This issue has been fixed in the .NET Framework 4.5.2 and may be addressed by upgrading to that version (or a later version) of the .NET Framework.","pos":[85548,85695]},{"content":"Alternatively, users can still drag scroll bars to the final items in these collections, but may need to try twice to do so successfully.","pos":[85696,85833]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[85838,85843]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[85844,85849]},{"content":"Version","pos":[85854,85861]},{"content":"4.5-4.5.2","pos":[85862,85871]},{"content":"Type","pos":[85876,85880]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[85881,85888]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[85893,85902]},{"content":"CD0113","pos":[85903,85909]},{"pos":[85951,86059],"content":"114: GlyphRun.ComputeInkBoundingBox() and FormattedText.Extent return different values beginning in .NET 4.5","linkify":"114: GlyphRun.ComputeInkBoundingBox() and FormattedText.Extent return different values beginning in .NET 4.5","nodes":[{"content":"114: GlyphRun.ComputeInkBoundingBox() and FormattedText.Extent return different values beginning in .NET 4.5","pos":[0,108]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[86080,86087]},{"content":"Improvements were made to GlyphRun.ComputeInkBoundingBox() and FormattedText.Extent in the .NET Framework 4.5 to address issues where the boxes were too small for the contained glyphs in some cases in the .NET Framework 4.0.","pos":[86088,86312]},{"content":"As a result of this, some bounding boxes will be larger beginning in the .NET Framework 4.5, resulting in subtle differences in UI layout.","pos":[86313,86451]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[86456,86466]},{"content":"Be aware that some glyph bounding box sizes have increased.","pos":[86467,86526]},{"content":"These changes will usually improve presentation and hit box testing, but if the older (pre-.NET 4.5) behavior is desired, it can be opted into by adding the following entry to the app.config file:","pos":[86527,86723]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[86824,86829]},{"content":"Edge","pos":[86830,86834]},{"content":"Version","pos":[86839,86846]},{"content":"4.5","pos":[86847,86850]},{"content":"Type","pos":[86855,86859]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[86860,86867]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[86872,86885]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[87060,87069]},{"content":"CD0114","pos":[87070,87076]},{"pos":[87118,87192],"content":"124: Calling DataGrid.CommitEdit from a CellEditEnding handler drops focus","linkify":"124: Calling DataGrid.CommitEdit from a CellEditEnding handler drops focus","nodes":[{"content":"124: Calling DataGrid.CommitEdit from a CellEditEnding handler drops focus","pos":[0,74]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[87213,87220]},{"content":"Calling DataGrid.CommitEdit from one of the DataGrid's CellEditEnding event handlers causes the DataGrid to lose focus.","pos":[87221,87340]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[87345,87355]},{"content":"This bug has been fixed in the .NET Framework 4.5.2, so it can be avoided by upgrading the .NET Framework.","pos":[87356,87462]},{"content":"Alternatively, it can be avoided by explicitly re-selecting the DataGrid after calling CommitEdit.","pos":[87463,87561]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[87566,87571]},{"content":"Edge","pos":[87572,87576]},{"content":"Version","pos":[87581,87588]},{"content":"4.5-4.5.2","pos":[87589,87598]},{"content":"Type","pos":[87603,87607]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[87608,87615]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[87620,87633]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[87868,87877]},{"content":"CD0124","pos":[87878,87884]},{"pos":[87926,88003],"content":"125: ASP.NET MVC now escapes spaces in strings passed in via route parameters","linkify":"125: ASP.NET MVC now escapes spaces in strings passed in via route parameters","nodes":[{"content":"125: ASP.NET MVC now escapes spaces in strings passed in via route parameters","pos":[0,77]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[88024,88031]},{"content":"In order to conform to RFC 2396, spaces in route paths are now escaped when populating action parameters from a route.","pos":[88032,88150]},{"content":"So, whereas  <ph id=\"ph1\">`/controller/action/some data`</ph> would previously match the route <ph id=\"ph2\">`/controller/action/{data}`</ph> and provide <ph id=\"ph3\">`some data`</ph> as the data parameter, it will now provide <ph id=\"ph4\">`some%20data`</ph> instead.","pos":[88151,88345],"source":" So, whereas  `/controller/action/some data` would previously match the route `/controller/action/{data}` and provide `some data` as the data parameter, it will now provide `some%20data` instead."},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[88350,88360]},{"content":"Code should be updated to unescape string parameters from a route.","pos":[88361,88427]},{"content":"If the original URI is needed, it can be accessed with the Request.RequestUri.OriginalString API.","pos":[88428,88525]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[88530,88535]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[88536,88541]},{"content":"Version","pos":[88546,88553]},{"content":"4.5.2","pos":[88554,88559]},{"content":"Type","pos":[88564,88568]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[88569,88576]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[88581,88594]},{"pos":[88595,88709],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>System.Web.Http.RouteAttribute<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/system.web.http.routeattribute(v=vs.118).aspx)</ept>","source":"[System.Web.Http.RouteAttribute](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/system.web.http.routeattribute(v=vs.118).aspx)"},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[88714,88723]},{"content":"CD0125","pos":[88724,88730]},{"pos":[88772,88858],"content":"127: VB.NET no longer supports partial namespace qualification for System.Windows APIs","linkify":"127: VB.NET no longer supports partial namespace qualification for System.Windows APIs","nodes":[{"content":"127: VB.NET no longer supports partial namespace qualification for System.Windows APIs","pos":[0,86]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[88879,88886]},{"content":"Beginning in .NET 4.5.2, VB.NET projects cannot specify System.Windows APIs with partially-qualified namespaces.","pos":[88887,88999]},{"content":"For example, referring to <ph id=\"ph1\">`Windows.Forms.DialogResult`</ph> will fail.","pos":[89000,89065],"source":" For example, referring to `Windows.Forms.DialogResult` will fail."},{"content":"Instead, code must refer to the fully qualified name (<ph id=\"ph1\">`System.Windows.Forms.DialogResult`</ph>) or import the specific namespace and refer simply to <ph id=\"ph2\">`DialogResult`</ph>.","pos":[89066,89225],"source":" Instead, code must refer to the fully qualified name (`System.Windows.Forms.DialogResult`) or import the specific namespace and refer simply to `DialogResult`."},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[89230,89240]},{"pos":[89241,89392],"content":"Code should be updated to refer to <ph id=\"ph1\">`System.Windows`</ph> APIs either with simple names (and importing the relevant namespace) or with fully qualified names.","source":"Code should be updated to refer to `System.Windows` APIs either with simple names (and importing the relevant namespace) or with fully qualified names."},{"content":"Scope","pos":[89397,89402]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[89403,89408]},{"content":"Version","pos":[89413,89420]},{"content":"4.5.2","pos":[89421,89426]},{"content":"Type","pos":[89431,89435]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[89436,89447]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[89452,89461]},{"content":"CD0127","pos":[89462,89468]},{"pos":[89510,89591],"content":"129: Two-way data-binding to a property with a non-public setter is not supported","linkify":"129: Two-way data-binding to a property with a non-public setter is not supported","nodes":[{"content":"129: Two-way data-binding to a property with a non-public setter is not supported","pos":[0,81]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[89612,89619]},{"content":"Attempting to data bind to a property without a public setter has never been a supported scenario.","pos":[89620,89718]},{"content":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.5.1, this scenario will throw an InvalidOperationException.","pos":[89719,89812]},{"content":"Note that this new exception will only be thrown for apps that specifically target the .NET Framework 4.5.1.","pos":[89813,89921]},{"content":"If an app targets the .NET Framework 4.5, the call will be allowed.","pos":[89922,89989]},{"content":"If the app does not target a particular .NET Framework version, the binding will be treated as one-way.","pos":[89990,90093]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[90098,90108]},{"content":"The app should be updated to either use one-way binding, or expose the property's setter publicly.","pos":[90109,90207]},{"content":"Alternatively, targeting the .NET Framework 4.5 will cause the app to exhibit the old behavior.","pos":[90208,90303]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[90308,90313]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[90314,90319]},{"content":"Version","pos":[90324,90331]},{"content":"4.5.1","pos":[90332,90337]},{"content":"Type","pos":[90342,90346]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[90347,90358]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[90363,90376]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[90445,90454]},{"content":"CD0129","pos":[90455,90461]},{"pos":[90503,90578],"content":"130: Marshal.SizeOf and Marshal.PtrToStructure overloads break dynamic code","linkify":"130: Marshal.SizeOf and Marshal.PtrToStructure overloads break dynamic code","nodes":[{"content":"130: Marshal.SizeOf and Marshal.PtrToStructure overloads break dynamic code","pos":[0,75]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[90599,90606]},{"pos":[90607,90948],"content":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.5.1, dynamically binding to the methods <ph id=\"ph1\">`Marshal.SizeOf`</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">`Marshal.PtrToStructure`</ph> (via Windows PowerShell, IronPython, or the C# dynamic keyword, for example) can result in <ph id=\"ph3\">`MethodInvocationExceptions`</ph> because new overloads of these methods have been added that may be ambiguous to the scripting engines.","source":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.5.1, dynamically binding to the methods `Marshal.SizeOf` or `Marshal.PtrToStructure` (via Windows PowerShell, IronPython, or the C# dynamic keyword, for example) can result in `MethodInvocationExceptions` because new overloads of these methods have been added that may be ambiguous to the scripting engines."},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[90953,90963]},{"content":"Update scripts to clearly indicate which overload shouldbe used.","pos":[90964,91028]},{"content":"This can typically done by explicitly casting the methods' type parameters as <ph id=\"ph1\">`System.Type`</ph>.","pos":[91029,91121],"source":" This can typically done by explicitly casting the methods' type parameters as `System.Type`."},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>this link<ept id=\"p1\">](https://support.microsoft.com/kb/2909958/)</ept> for more detail and examples of how to workaround the issue.","pos":[91122,91241],"source":" See [this link](https://support.microsoft.com/kb/2909958/) for more detail and examples of how to workaround the issue."},{"content":"Scope","pos":[91246,91251]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[91252,91257]},{"content":"Version","pos":[91262,91269]},{"content":"4.5.1","pos":[91270,91275]},{"content":"Type","pos":[91280,91284]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[91285,91292]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[91297,91306]},{"content":"CD0130","pos":[91307,91313]},{"pos":[91355,91454],"content":"131: PreviewLostKeyboardFocus is called repeatedly if its handler shows a Windows Forms message box","linkify":"131: PreviewLostKeyboardFocus is called repeatedly if its handler shows a Windows Forms message box","nodes":[{"content":"131: PreviewLostKeyboardFocus is called repeatedly if its handler shows a Windows Forms message box","pos":[0,99]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[91475,91482]},{"pos":[91483,91744],"content":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.5, calling <ph id=\"ph1\">`System.Windows.Forms.MessageBox.Show`</ph> from a <ph id=\"ph2\">`UIElement.PreviewLostKeyboardFocus`</ph> handler will cause the handler to re-fire when the message box is closed, potentially resulting in an infinite loop of message boxes.","source":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.5, calling `System.Windows.Forms.MessageBox.Show` from a `UIElement.PreviewLostKeyboardFocus` handler will cause the handler to re-fire when the message box is closed, potentially resulting in an infinite loop of message boxes."},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[91749,91759]},{"content":"There are two options to work around this issue -","pos":[91760,91809]},{"content":"It may be avoided by calling <ph id=\"ph1\">`System.Windows.MessageBox.Show`</ph> instead of <ph id=\"ph2\">`System.Windows.Forms.MessageBox.Show`</ph>.","pos":[91822,91934],"source":" It may be avoided by calling `System.Windows.MessageBox.Show` instead of `System.Windows.Forms.MessageBox.Show`."},{"content":"It may be avoided by showing the message box from a <ph id=\"ph1\">`LostKeyboardFocus`</ph> event handler (as opposed to a <ph id=\"ph2\">`PreviewLostKeyboardFocus`</ph> event handler).","pos":[91947,92092],"source":" It may be avoided by showing the message box from a `LostKeyboardFocus` event handler (as opposed to a `PreviewLostKeyboardFocus` event handler)."},{"content":"Scope","pos":[92097,92102]},{"content":"Edge","pos":[92103,92107]},{"content":"Version","pos":[92112,92119]},{"content":"4.5","pos":[92120,92123]},{"content":"Type","pos":[92128,92132]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[92133,92140]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[92145,92158]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[92538,92547]},{"content":"CD0131","pos":[92548,92554]},{"pos":[92596,92723],"content":"133: A ConcurrentDictionary serialized in .NET 4.5 with NetDataContractSerializer cannot be deserialized by .NET 4.5.1 or 4.5.2","linkify":"133: A ConcurrentDictionary serialized in .NET 4.5 with NetDataContractSerializer cannot be deserialized by .NET 4.5.1 or 4.5.2","nodes":[{"content":"133: A ConcurrentDictionary serialized in .NET 4.5 with NetDataContractSerializer cannot be deserialized by .NET 4.5.1 or 4.5.2","pos":[0,127]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[92744,92751]},{"content":"Due to internal changes to the type, <ph id=\"ph1\">`System.Collections.Concurrent.ConcurrentDictionary`</ph> objects that are serialized with the .NET Framework 4.5 using the <ph id=\"ph2\">`NetDataContractSerializer`</ph> cannot be deserialized in the .NET Framework 4.5.1 or in the .NET Framework 4.5.2.","pos":[92752,93018],"source":"Due to internal changes to the type, `System.Collections.Concurrent.ConcurrentDictionary` objects that are serialized with the .NET Framework 4.5 using the `NetDataContractSerializer` cannot be deserialized in the .NET Framework 4.5.1 or in the .NET Framework 4.5.2."},{"content":"Note that moving the other direction (serializing with the .NET Framework 4.5.x and deserializing with the .NET Framework 4.5) works.","pos":[93031,93164]},{"content":"Similarly, all 4.x cross-version serialization works with the .NET Framework 4.6.","pos":[93165,93246]},{"content":"Serializing and deserializing with a single version of the .NET Framework is not affected.","pos":[93259,93349]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[93354,93364]},{"content":"If it is necessary to serialize and deserialize a ConcurrentDictionary between the .NET Framework 4.5 and .NET Framework 4.5.1/4.5.2, an alternate serializer like the DataContractSerializer or BinaryFormatter serializer should be used instead of the NetDataContractSerializer.","pos":[93365,93641]},{"content":"Alternatively, because this issue is addressed in the .NET Framework 4.6, it may be solved by upgrading to that version of the .NET Framework.","pos":[93654,93796]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[93801,93806]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[93807,93812]},{"content":"Version","pos":[93817,93824]},{"content":"4.5.1-4.6","pos":[93825,93834]},{"content":"Type","pos":[93839,93843]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[93844,93851]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[93856,93865]},{"content":"CD0133","pos":[93866,93872]},{"pos":[93914,93970],"content":"134: Persian calendar now uses the Hijri solar algorithm","linkify":"134: Persian calendar now uses the Hijri solar algorithm","nodes":[{"content":"134: Persian calendar now uses the Hijri solar algorithm","pos":[0,56]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[93991,93998]},{"content":"Starting with the .NET Framework 4.6, the PersianCalendar class uses the Hijri solar algorithm.","pos":[93999,94094]},{"content":"Converting dates between the PersianCalendar and other calendars may produce a slightly different result beginning with the .NET Framework 4.6 for dates earlier than 1800 or later than 2023 (Gregorian).","pos":[94095,94297]},{"content":"Also, <ph id=\"ph1\">`PersianCalendar.MinSupportedDateTime`</ph> is now <ph id=\"ph2\">`March 22, 0622 instead of March 21, 0622`</ph>.","pos":[94310,94405],"source":" Also, `PersianCalendar.MinSupportedDateTime` is now `March 22, 0622 instead of March 21, 0622`."},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[94410,94420]},{"content":"Be aware that some early or late dates may be slightly different when using the PersianCalendar in .NET 4.6.","pos":[94421,94529]},{"content":"Also, when serializing dates between processes which may run on different .NET Framework versions, do not store them as PersianCalendar date strings (since those values may be different).","pos":[94530,94717]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[94722,94727]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[94728,94733]},{"content":"Version","pos":[94738,94745]},{"content":"4.6","pos":[94746,94749]},{"content":"Type","pos":[94754,94758]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[94759,94766]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[94771,94784]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[94858,94867]},{"content":"CD0134","pos":[94868,94874]},{"pos":[94916,94995],"content":"138: Calling CreateDefaultAuthorizationContext with a null argument has changed","linkify":"138: Calling CreateDefaultAuthorizationContext with a null argument has changed","nodes":[{"content":"138: Calling CreateDefaultAuthorizationContext with a null argument has changed","pos":[0,79]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[95016,95023]},{"pos":[95024,95262],"content":"The implementation of the AuthorizationContext returned by a call to the <ph id=\"ph1\">`CreateDefaultAuthorizationContext(IList&lt;IAuthorizationPolicy&gt;)`</ph> with a null authorizationPolicies argument has changed its implementation in the .NET Framework 4.6.","source":"The implementation of the AuthorizationContext returned by a call to the `CreateDefaultAuthorizationContext(IList<IAuthorizationPolicy>)` with a null authorizationPolicies argument has changed its implementation in the .NET Framework 4.6."},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[95267,95277]},{"content":"In rare cases, WCF apps that use custom authentication may see behavioral differences.","pos":[95278,95364]},{"content":"In such cases, the previous behavior can be restored in either of two ways:","pos":[95365,95440]},{"content":"Recompile your app to target an earlier version of the .NET Framework than 4.6.","pos":[95453,95532]},{"content":"For IIS-hosted services, use the <ph id=\"ph1\">\\&lt;</ph>httpRuntime targetFramework=\"x.x\" /&gt; element to target an earlier version of the .NET Framework.","pos":[95533,95664],"source":" For IIS-hosted services, use the \\<httpRuntime targetFramework=\"x.x\" /> element to target an earlier version of the .NET Framework."},{"content":"Add the following line to the <ph id=\"ph1\">`&lt;appSettings&gt;`</ph> section of your app.config file: <ph id=\"ph2\">`&lt;add key=\"appContext.SetSwitch:Switch.System.IdentityModel.EnableCachedEmptyDefaultAuthorizationContext\" value=\"true\" /&gt;`</ph>","pos":[95677,95878],"source":" Add the following line to the `<appSettings>` section of your app.config file: `<add key=\"appContext.SetSwitch:Switch.System.IdentityModel.EnableCachedEmptyDefaultAuthorizationContext\" value=\"true\" />`"},{"content":"Scope","pos":[95883,95888]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[95889,95894]},{"content":"Version","pos":[95899,95906]},{"content":"4.6","pos":[95907,95910]},{"content":"Type","pos":[95915,95919]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[95920,95931]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[95936,95949]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[96161,96170]},{"content":"CD0138","pos":[96171,96177]},{"pos":[96219,96271],"content":"141: WPF TreeViewItem must be used within a TreeView","linkify":"141: WPF TreeViewItem must be used within a TreeView","nodes":[{"content":"141: WPF TreeViewItem must be used within a TreeView","pos":[0,52]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[96292,96299]},{"content":"A change was introduced in 4.5 that restricts usage of TreeViewItem elements outside of a TreeView.","pos":[96300,96399]},{"content":"This manifests under the following conditions:","pos":[96400,96446]},{"content":"TreeViewItem's visual parent is not a panel.","pos":[96459,96503]},{"content":"(A TreeViewItem generated for a TreeView will have a panel as its parent)","pos":[96504,96577]},{"content":"The TreeViewItem is a descendant of a VirtualizingStackPanel acting as the \"items host\" for a list control (ListBox, DataGrid, ListView, etc.).","pos":[96590,96733]},{"content":"Virtualization doesn't need to be enabled.","pos":[96734,96776]},{"content":"The VirtualizingStackPanel is item-scrolling (<ph id=\"ph1\">`ScrollUnit=\"Item\"`</ph>).","pos":[96789,96856],"source":" The VirtualizingStackPanel is item-scrolling (`ScrollUnit=\"Item\"`)."},{"content":"Someone calls <ph id=\"ph1\">`VirtualizingStackPanel.MakeVisible(v)`</ph> to scroll an element <ph id=\"ph2\">`v`</ph> into view.","pos":[96869,96958],"source":" Someone calls `VirtualizingStackPanel.MakeVisible(v)` to scroll an element `v` into view."},{"content":"This can be done explicitly, or implicitly in a number of ways; perhaps the most common way is simply clicking on <ph id=\"ph1\">`v`</ph> to give it the keyboard focus.","pos":[96959,97107],"source":" This can be done explicitly, or implicitly in a number of ways; perhaps the most common way is simply clicking on `v` to give it the keyboard focus."},{"content":"The visual-parent chain from <ph id=\"ph1\">`v`</ph> to the VirtualizingStackPanel passes through the TreeViewItem.","pos":[97120,97215],"source":" The visual-parent chain from `v` to the VirtualizingStackPanel passes through the TreeViewItem."},{"content":"In other words, this is seen when a TreeViewItem is used outside of a TreeView, and the user clicks on a descendant of the TreeViewItem to bring it into view.","pos":[97228,97386]},{"content":"If the TreeViewItem has no focusable descendants, you'll never see this issue.","pos":[97387,97465]},{"content":"An example of a situation where this is hit is when a TreeViewItem is the root of a DataTemplate.","pos":[97466,97563]},{"content":"When this issue is hit, there is an InvalidCastException that occurs within the WPF framework.","pos":[97565,97659]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[97664,97674]},{"content":"A hotfix will be made available for this.","pos":[97675,97716]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[97721,97726]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[97727,97732]},{"content":"Version","pos":[97737,97744]},{"content":"4.5","pos":[97745,97748]},{"content":"Type","pos":[97753,97757]},{"content":"Runtime","pos":[97758,97765]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[97770,97779]},{"content":"CD0141","pos":[97780,97786]},{"pos":[97828,97892],"content":"143: X509CertificateClaimSet.FindClaims Considers All claimTypes","linkify":"143: X509CertificateClaimSet.FindClaims Considers All claimTypes","nodes":[{"content":"143: X509CertificateClaimSet.FindClaims Considers All claimTypes","pos":[0,64]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[97913,97920]},{"content":"In apps that target the .NET Framework 4.6.1, if an X509 claim set is initialized from a certificate that has multiple DNS entries in its SAN field, the FindClaims method attempts to match the claimType argument with all the DNS entries.","pos":[97921,98158]},{"content":"For apps that target previous versions of the .NET Framework, the FindClaims method attempts to match the claimType argument only with the last DNS entry.","pos":[98171,98325]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[98330,98340]},{"content":"This change only affects applications targeting the .NET Framework 4.6.1.","pos":[98341,98414]},{"content":"This change may be disabled (or enabled if targetting pre-4.6.1) with the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DisableMultipleDNSEntries<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/mt620030%28v=vs.110%29.aspx)</ept> compatibility switch.","pos":[98415,98602],"source":" This change may be disabled (or enabled if targetting pre-4.6.1) with the [DisableMultipleDNSEntries](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/mt620030%28v=vs.110%29.aspx) compatibility switch."},{"content":"Scope","pos":[98607,98612]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[98613,98618]},{"content":"Version","pos":[98623,98630]},{"content":"4.6.1","pos":[98631,98636]},{"content":"Type","pos":[98641,98645]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[98646,98657]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[98662,98675]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[98810,98819]},{"content":"CD0143","pos":[98820,98826]},{"pos":[98868,98981],"content":"144: Application.FilterMessage no longer throws for re-entrant implementations of IMessageFilter.PreFilterMessage","linkify":"144: Application.FilterMessage no longer throws for re-entrant implementations of IMessageFilter.PreFilterMessage","nodes":[{"content":"144: Application.FilterMessage no longer throws for re-entrant implementations of IMessageFilter.PreFilterMessage","pos":[0,113]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[99002,99009]},{"content":"Prior to the .NET Framework 4.6.1, calling Application.FilterMessage with an IMessageFilter.PreFilterMessage which called AddMessageFilter or RemoveMessageFilter (while also calling Application.DoEvents) would cause an IndexOutOfRangeException.","pos":[99010,99254]},{"content":"Beginning with applications targeting the .NET Framework 4.6.1, this exception is no longer thrown, and re-entrant filters as described above may be used.","pos":[99267,99421]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[99426,99436]},{"content":"Be aware that Application.FilterMessage will no longer throw for the re-entrant IMessageFilter.PreFilterMessage behavior described above.","pos":[99437,99574]},{"content":"This only affects applications targeting the .NET Framework 4.6.1.","pos":[99575,99641]},{"content":"Apps targeting the .NET Framework 4.6.1 can opt out of this change (or apps targeting older Frameworks may opt in) by using the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DontSupportReentrantFilterMessage<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/mt620032%28v=vs.110%29.aspx)</ept> compatibility switch.","pos":[99654,99903],"source":" Apps targeting the .NET Framework 4.6.1 can opt out of this change (or apps targeting older Frameworks may opt in) by using the [DontSupportReentrantFilterMessage](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/mt620032%28v=vs.110%29.aspx) compatibility switch."},{"content":"Scope","pos":[99908,99913]},{"content":"Edge","pos":[99914,99918]},{"content":"Version","pos":[99923,99930]},{"content":"4.6.1","pos":[99931,99936]},{"content":"Type","pos":[99941,99945]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[99946,99957]},{"content":"Affected APIs","pos":[99962,99975]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[100096,100105]},{"content":"CD0144","pos":[100106,100112]},{"pos":[100154,100223],"content":"145: CurrentCulture is not preserved across WPF Dispatcher operations","linkify":"145: CurrentCulture is not preserved across WPF Dispatcher operations","nodes":[{"content":"145: CurrentCulture is not preserved across WPF Dispatcher operations","pos":[0,69]}]},{"content":"Details","pos":[100244,100251]},{"content":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.6, changes to CurrentCulture or CurrentUICulture made within a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Dispatcher<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/system.windows.threading.dispatcher%28v=vs.110%29.aspx)</ept> will be lost at the end of that dispatcher operation.","pos":[100252,100506],"source":"Beginning in the .NET Framework 4.6, changes to CurrentCulture or CurrentUICulture made within a [Dispatcher](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/system.windows.threading.dispatcher%28v=vs.110%29.aspx) will be lost at the end of that dispatcher operation."},{"content":"Similarly, changes to CurrentCulture or CurrentUICulture made outside of a Dispatcher operation may not be reflected when that operation executes.","pos":[100507,100653]},{"content":"Practically speaking, this means that CurrentCulture and CurrentUICulture changes may not flow between WPF UI callbacks and other code in a WPF application.","pos":[100666,100822]},{"content":"This is due to a change in <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>ExecutionContext<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/system.threading.executioncontext%28v=vs.110%29.aspx)</ept> that causes CurrentCulture and CurrentUICulture to be stored in the execution context beginning with apps targeting the .NET Framework 4.6.","pos":[100835,101109],"source":" This is due to a change in [ExecutionContext](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/system.threading.executioncontext%28v=vs.110%29.aspx) that causes CurrentCulture and CurrentUICulture to be stored in the execution context beginning with apps targeting the .NET Framework 4.6."},{"content":"WPF dispatcher operations store the execution context used to begin the operation and restore the previous context when the operation is completed.","pos":[101110,101257]},{"content":"Because CurrentCulture and CurrentUICulture are now part of that context, changes to them within a dispatcher operation are not persisted outside of the operation.","pos":[101258,101421]},{"content":"Suggestion","pos":[101426,101436]},{"content":"Apps affected by this change may work around it by storing the desired CurrentCulture or CurrentUICulture in a field and checking in all Dispatcher operation bodies (including UI event callback handlers) that the correct CurrentCulture and CurrentUICulture are set.","pos":[101437,101702]},{"content":"Alternatively, because the ExecutionContext change underlying this WPF change only affects apps targeting the .NET Framework 4.6 or newer, this break can be avoided by targeting the .NET Framework 4.5.2.","pos":[101703,101906]},{"content":"Scope","pos":[101911,101916]},{"content":"Minor","pos":[101917,101922]},{"content":"Version","pos":[101927,101934]},{"content":"4.6","pos":[101935,101938]},{"content":"Type","pos":[101943,101947]},{"content":"Retargeting","pos":[101948,101959]},{"content":"Analyzers","pos":[101964,101973]},{"content":"CD0145","pos":[101974,101980]}]}